# Task: Implement `apply_duration/2`

Implement the private `apply_duration/2` helper in `Clock.Fake`.

Given a base `datetime` (a `DateTime`) and a `duration` keyword list such as
`[seconds: 30]` or `[hours: 1, minutes: 30]`, return a new `DateTime` that is
`datetime` shifted forward by the total duration. Each key is a time unit and
its value is an integer amount. Supported units are `:second`/`:seconds`,
`:minute`/`:minutes`, `:hour`/`:hours`, and `:day`/`:days`, whose second-values
are provided by the module attribute `@unit_seconds`.

Convert the whole duration to a total number of seconds by summing
`amount * @unit_seconds[unit]` across every `{unit, amount}` pair (use
`Map.fetch!/2` so an unknown unit raises), then apply the shift once with
`DateTime.add(datetime, total, :second)`. Applying the total in one call keeps
the behaviour robust across Elixir versions regardless of which units
`DateTime.add/3` supports natively.

```elixir
